**Marvell Technology Inc (MRVL.O)- ASIC Lumpiness Drives Data Center Miss;** **Thesis Remains Intact**

MRVL stock was -11% after reporting results/guide in-line with Street and our preview adjusting for the ~$60M auto ethernet divestment. However, data center biz was modestly below expectations due to optics timing and was guided flat below Citi/Street +5% qq expectations due to lumpiness in the ASIC sales spooking investor concerns on potential share shifts in the Trainium program. We view MRVL's DC comments as customer concentration driven and not a broad read on the AI demand. Management's comments on record XPU/XPU attach design momentum indicates no major share shifts at its XPU customers. We adjust our CY25/26 EPS -1%/-5% on lower gross margins due to higher ASIC mix and reduce TP to $92 on consistent 27x P/E times revised CY26 EPS of $3.39. We expect the stock to recover going into Citi's Global TMT conference where we host the management for a fireside chat on 9/3. Maintain Buy.

2Q EPS beat cons, driven by GM +137bps (with 108bps from shrink vs 61bps benefit in 1Q). 2Q comps were roughly in- line at \(+2.8\%\) vs cons \(+2.6\%\) , and even though traffic was \(+1.5\%\) (vs 1Q - 0.3%), this was due to easier comparisons in 2Q, and 2Q comps decelerated on a 2- yr basis (2Q \(+3.3\%\) vs 1Q \(+4.9\%\) ). Mgmt indicated they are seeing consumer resilience across income cohorts with middle- and upper- income brackets gravitating towards value in the discretionary categories. DG has mindshare for value and is seeing a benefit from their shrink initiatives; however, long- term we still have our concerns that DG is going to struggle to achieve its \(6 - 7\%\) EBIT margin goal (vs F25E EBIT margin of \(4.8\%\) ) in a world where WMT's ability to deliver value and convenience is driving market share gains. With shares trading at 9.6x F25E EV/EBITDA, we view the risk/reward as balanced.
Paul Lejuez, CFA, CPA

2Q EPS \(\) 5.80\(was a big beat vs cons\) \ \(5.07\) driven from strong comps \((+6.7\%)\) vs cons \(+2.6\%\) and stronger GM. Mgmt raised F25 guidance from \(\) 22.65- 23.20\(to\) \ \(23.85 - 24.30\) , accounting for the stronger than planned 2Q and higher 2H comps. Mgmt is ramping investment spending in to support long- term growth initiatives (wellness, store experience, int'l, marketplace), which will weigh on margins. However, we expect 2H com g uidance to prove very conservative and expect F25 EPS of \(\) 25+\(. A big bright spot in 2Q was strength of prestige makeup + LSD, an improvement vs 1Q flat, and suggests competitive pressures continue to abate and the product pipeline is strong. ULTA is showing they can differentiate themselves w/a better brand assortment/marketing/promo strategy, leaving us more positive on the biz. However, with shares trading at a P/E multiple of 19x our above cons F25E, we see a balanced risk/reward at current levels.
Kelly Crago, CFA | Paul Lejeuz, CFA, CPA

tranche of tariffs vs prior guidance (now saying vast majority of first round mitigated vs \(55\%\) assumption prior). With further mitigation expected in F26, mgmt does not expect any incremental EBIT margin pressure from tariffs (on full yr basis). However, pricing is now cited as a mitigation tool (it wasn't previously), which leaves us cautious. 3QTD comps are seemingly at least as strong as 2Q at Gap/ON, but margin headwinds from tariffs into 1H26 limit EPS upside. We view risk/reward as balanced.
Paul Lejeuz, CFA, CPA

We remain more cautious on CRM with partner feedback in F2Q suggesting an underwhelming demand picture: top- of- funnel activity is progressively weakening but there are still instances of ACV growth. Agentforce interest persists, though large- scale rollouts are rare, consistent with intra- Q takeaways at the Agentforce Boston event. We await more data points around wider rollouts and commercialization before turning constructive. We expect revenue growth to remain constrained in the HSD near- term, with limited Q2 upside. We believe price increases were likely already embedded in guidance. We remain Neutral- rated, though our PT lowers to \(\) 275\(from\) \ \(295\) implying \(- 17xFY27FCF\) with limited estimate changes and a slightly higher valuation discount for increased competition.
FQ2 Partner Checks Summary
CRM - Quarterly Trends and F2Q Estimates

We expect results over the coming three months to outpace consensus expectations, leading to positive revisions to 2026 estimates. Now that top- line growth has moderated, we believe positive EPS revisions, driven by margins (better for longer), will positively impact sentiment and valuation. We remain almost \(10\%\) above consensus looking forward over the next 12 months.

Dell shares were down \(\sim 5\%\) as upside from AI server revenues was partially offset by weaker storage, traditional server and PC segment revenues. July quarter margins were negatively impacted from a higher AI contribution mix and one- time costs associated with expedited shipping. Management raised CY25 (FY26) AI revenue expectations to \(\sim \$ 20bn\) (doubling y) with strong backlog comprising of growing contribution from enterprise and sovereign which bodes well for storage/services attach and margins ahead. FY26 revenue and EPS guide raise embodies higher AI server revenue contribution \((+5bn)\) partially offset with weakness in traditional server and storage \((\sim \$ 1bn)\) , albeit with improving margins in 2H. Our estimates undergo minor changes, and we maintain our Buy rating, Target Price at \(\) 160\(. Management will be meeting with investors at Citi's Global TMT conference next week and will be hosting an Analyst meeting on Oct 7th.
Dell's AI Order and Backlog
Quarterly Results and Revisions, vs Street and Citi

OLLI delivered a strong 2Q SSS and EPS beat. We were concerned the bar was high for 2Q in our preview (see here) - that played out more/less as expected judging by today's lackluster stock reaction. With this event now behind us, the setup looks better for the stock. Demand momentum is clearly continuing and new 2H SSS guidance looks beatable, the gross margin strength & guidance raise shows OLLI gaining scale with its vendors, the merchandise availability is getting more attractive from tariff disruption, and unit growth is accelerating with mgmt. citing improving new store economics. We view OLLI as one of the best momentum stories in retail right now. We raise our estimates \(>\) new guidance and take our TP to \(\) 154\(based on rolling forward the stock's FY1 multiple of - 34x to our new FY26 EPS of\) \ \(4.54\) (16% growth y/y).

After connecting with the Tower firms and the large- cap Telcos, including T- Mobile management and Verizon IR, we have some additional takeaways and implications from the announced spectrum purchase by AT&T. We view additional spectrum sales by EchoStar as the writing on the wall that the company is shuttering its facilities- based 5G strategy and migrating to a hybrid operator (aka MVNO). For AT&T, we view the deal as a net positive. Beyond enhancing long- term industry structure, the use of spectrum for incremental capacity over densification for a few years should provide \(\) 2.5B\(of run - rate annual savings within five years, representing an annual help to EBITDA of about 100bps. For towers, we think the risk beyond losing EchoStar revenue (or roughly a year of growth) is that underlying organic growth slows by roughly 100bps to 4% instead of a 5% base - case while the incremental spectral capacity gets absorbed by the national carriers.
Michael Rollins, CFA | Nick Joseph
Bull/Bear: EchoStar Corporation

This week both HP and Dell reported earnings. HP posted sales above Consensus driven by strength in its PC segment while Dell's PC segment sales were below Consensus by \(3\%\) . Asiya Merchant, our hardware analyst, believes that Dell likely lost share in PCs. Dell raised its F26 AI server shipment guidance from \(\) 15\(billion to\) \ \(20\) billion, which we believe is good for NVDA ( \(88\%\) of sales) and MU ( \(17\%\) of sales). Dell expects the traditional server business to grow in the 2nd half but below their prior expectations from the beginning of the year. We believe this is a mild negative for AMD ( \(29\%\) of sales) and INTC ( \(25\%\) of sales). Microchip remains our top pick with other Buy- rated names including AVGO, ADI, MU, NXPI, and TXN. Christopher Danely

Second quarter GDP was revised higher in the second release of data, from \(3.0\%\) to \(3.3\%\) with final private domestic demand revised from \(1.2\%\) to \(1.9\%\) . But details of revisions do not change the story that underlying demand is slowing outside of a few specific parts of the economy. Upward revisions came largely from intellectual property product and business equipment investment, which have been strong in recent quarters possibly due to strong demand for AI investment. While this trend could continue, we are skeptical that strong investment in this sector will support economic activity more broadly. Consumption was revised modestly higher but services consumption growing just \(1.2\%\) in Q2 has clearly slowed compared to recent years. We expect underlying growth will slow further as the labor market weakens and tariff costs increasingly weigh on activity.
Final private domestic demand was revised higher, largely due to investment
Strong business equipment investment has correlated with imports of computers

After the July employment report made clear the downside risks to the labor market, we expect continued gradual weakening in August data, with 45k payrolls added and the unemployment rate rising to \(4.3\%\) with upside risk. This should be soft enough to all but ensure a rate cut from the Fed in September. Still, data over the last 3- 4 months have not reflected a sharp weakening in the labor market, with the chance remaining that contracting labor supply limits the increase in the unemployment rate or that hiring picks up after a period of uncertainty. But rising continuing jobless claims and a new high in consumers describing jobs as "hard to get" lead us to think the trend of hiring still worsened in August. Continued softening in the labor market into the fall would be a clear signal that a series of rate cuts is likely after September.
Veronica Clark | Andrew Hollenhorst
Key indicators of the unemployment rate suggest hiring weakened further in August

Initial jobless claims decreased to \(229k\) , while continuing claims fell to 1954k. Jobless claims data continue to depict a labor market characterized by low churn, with initial claims remaining low, indicating layoffs are not rising in a concerning manner, but also hiring remaining soft with continuing claims at higher levels relative to earlier in the year. We expect the upcoming jobs report will reflect weaker labor demand, and project an increase in the unemployment rate to \(4.3\%\) in August. We expect modest nonfarm payroll growth of \(45k\) . This data would shift the balance of risks in the Fed mandate more toward the labor market side and would make a September rate cut very likely.
Gisela Young | Andrew Hollenhorst | Veronica Clark  Initial jobless claims similar to levels in recent years

Citi Research stock recommendations include an investment rating and an optional risk rating to highlight high risk stocks. Risk rating takes into account both price volatility and fundamental criteria. Stocks will either have no risk rating or a High risk rating assigned.

Investment Ratings: Citi Research investment ratings are Buy, Neutral and Sell. Our ratings are a function of analyst expectations of expected total return ("ETR") and risk. ETR is the sum of the forecast price appreciation (or depreciation) plus the dividend yield for a stock within the next 12 months. The target price is based on a 12 month time horizon. The Investment rating definitions are: Buy (1) ETR of 15% or more or 25% or more for High risk stocks; and Sell (3) for negative ETR. Any covered stock not assigned a Buy or a Sell is a Neutral (2). For stocks rated Neutral (2), if an analyst believes that there are insufficient

valuation drivers and/or investment catalysts to derive a positive or negative investment view, they may elect with the approval of Citi Research management not to assign a target price and, thus, not derive an ETR. Citi Research may suspend its rating and target price and assign "Rating Suspended" status for regulatory and/or internal policy reasons. Citi Research may also suspend its rating and target price and assign "Under Review" status for other exceptional circumstances (e.g. lack of information critical to the analyst's thesis, trading suspension) affecting the company and/or trading in the company's securities. In both such situations, the rating and target price will show as "- " and "- " respectively in the rating history price chart. Prior to 11 April 2022 Citi Research assigned "Under Review" status to both situations and prior to 11 Nov 2020 only in exceptional circumstances. As soon as practically possible, the analyst will publish a note re- establishing a rating and investment thesis. Investment ratings are determined by the ranges described above at the time of initiation of coverage, a change in investment and/or risk rating, or a change in target price (subject to limited management discretion). At times, the expected total returns may fall outside of these ranges because of market price movements and/or other short- term volatility or trading patterns. Such interim deviations will be permitted but will become subject to review by Research Management. Your decision to buy or sell a security should be based upon your personal investment objectives and should be made only after evaluating the stock's expected performance and risk.

Catalyst Watch and STV Upside/Downside calls: Citi Research may also include a Catalyst Watch or STV Upside or Downside call to indicate the analyst expects the share price to rise (fall) in absolute terms over a specified period of 30 or 90 days in reaction to one or more specific near- term catalysts or events impacting the company or the market. A Catalyst Watch will be published when Analyst confidence is high that an impact to share price will occur; it will be a STV when confidence level is moderate. A Catalyst Watch or STV Upside/Downside call will automatically expire at the end of the specified 30/90 day period. The Catalyst Watch will also be automatically removed if share price performance (calculated at market close) exceeds 15% against the direction of the call (unless over- ridden by the analyst). The analyst may also remove a Catalyst Watch or STV call prior to the end of the specified period in a published research note. A Catalyst Watch/STV Upside or Downside call may be different from and does not affect a stock's fundamental equity rating, which reflects a longer- term total absolute return expectation. For purposes of FINRA ratings- distribution- disclosure rules, a Catalyst Watch/STV Upside call corresponds to a buy recommendation and a Catalyst Watch/STV Downside call corresponds to a sell recommendation. Any stock not assigned to a Catalyst Watch Upside, Catalyst Watch Downside, STV Upside, or STV Downside call is considered Catalyst Watch/STV No View. For purposes of FINRA ratings distribution- disclosure rules, we correspond Catalyst Watch/STV No View to Hold in our ratings distribution table for our Catalyst Watch/STV Upside/Downside rating system. However, we reiterate that we do not consider No View to be a recommendation. For all Catalyst Watch/STV Upside/Downside calls, risk exists that the catalyst(s) and associated share- price movement will not materialize as expected.
